Next.js Routing
................

Routing in Next.js is a built-in, file-based system that automatically maps URLs to files and folders, making navigation simple, fast, and efficient without extra libraries.

Uses file-based routing via the pages/ or app/ directory with no extra setup.
Supports dynamic and nested routes through folder and file naming.
Provides fast navigation using the built-in Link component with preloading.
Allows redirects, SEO-friendly URLs, and optimized performance by default.

Routing = which page/code runs when a user visits a URL.


Types of Routes in Next.js
..........................

1. Static Route — Fixed URL

src/app/about/page.tsx        →  /about

2. Nested Route — URL with sub-pages

Just keep creating folders inside folders
src/app/dashboard/page.tsx           →  /dashboard
src/app/dashboard/settings/page.tsx  →  /dashboard/settings
src/app/dashboard/profile/page.tsx   →  /dashboard/profile

3. Dynamic Route — Variable in URL

src/app/blog/[slug]/page.tsx     →  /blog/hello-world
                                 →  /blog/my-post
                                 →  /blog/anything

src/app/users/[id]/page.tsx      →  /users/1
                                 →  /users/42
                                 →  /users/999

4. Catch-all Route — Multiple URL segments

src/app/docs/[...slug]/page.tsx   →  /docs/intro
                                  →  /docs/react/hooks
                                  →  /docs/a/b/c/d


5. Optional Catch-all — With or without segments

src/app/shop/[[...filters]]/page.tsx  →  /shop             (no filters)
                                      →  /shop/men
                                      →  /shop/men/shoes


6. Route Groups — Organise without affecting URL

Wrap folder name in (parentheses) — no URL segment added:

src/app/(marketing)/page.tsx          →  /
src/app/(marketing)/about/page.tsx    →  /about
src/app/(dashboard)/home/page.tsx     →  /home
src/app/(dashboard)/settings/page.tsx →  /settings


7. API Route — Backend endpoint (no UI)
File must be named route.ts (not page.tsx):


src/app/api/users/route.ts          →  /api/users
src/app/api/users/[id]/route.ts     →  /api/users/42
src/app/api/posts/route.ts          →  /api/posts                                      


